<p>She told us that the night before, after Julio&rsquo;s mommy had tucked him in and his sister had fallen asleep, Julio had fastened a bath towel around his neck with a safety pin, opened his window, and jumped from his fifth-floor room to the sidewalk below.</p>

<p>My first thought was to be upset that I hadn&rsquo;t had the courage to go through with the plan first. Whenever I&rsquo;d tied a towel around my neck, I&rsquo;d only run up and down the halls with my arms out in front of me. Though I knew boys couldn&rsquo;t really fly, I also believed it was because they hadn&rsquo;t tried the proper way. And now that Julio had done it &mdash; had <em>tried</em> to fly and hadn&rsquo;t died, but only injured his head &mdash; I thought that I could succeed where he&rsquo;d failed.</p>

<p>After breakfast Mommy led Asia and me downstairs and across Creston Avenue to the front of Julio&rsquo;s building. I expected him and his mother to come out to greet us so we could talk about how brave her son was and marvel at his bandaged head, but they never came. Mommy just pointed to the dried blood on the concrete.</p>

<p>&ldquo;This is what happens to little boys who don&rsquo;t listen to their mommies,&rdquo; she said, her eyes still wet but her face as hard as a brick.</p>

<p>Asia started to cry. I didn&rsquo;t know why.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What kind of cape Julio had on?&rdquo; I asked Mommy, trying to figure out what I could do better than him when my time came at the windowsill.</p>

<p>The blow Mommy delivered to the side of my head &mdash; half on my cheek, half on my ear &mdash; rocked me to one side and rang in my skull. While I tried to understand why I&rsquo;d been hit, my mind&rsquo;s mind quickly went to work: it took the light that had flashed through my brain when she&rsquo;d struck me and produced an explosion caused by a car that had gone over a cliff. While Mommy shook me back and forth by the collar &mdash; Asia sobbing in the background &mdash; and spat, &ldquo;Boys! Can&rsquo;t! Fly! Can you hear me, God damn it? Can you hear what the hell I&rsquo;m saying?&rdquo; my mind&rsquo;s mind rewound the footage, and the sedan&rsquo;s body sucked the rolling flames back into itself. The warped doors and blasted glass reattached themselves, and the car rose back toward the cliff&rsquo;s edge, where it leveled off onto the ground, the split guardrail closing behind it like a pair of double doors. The car slid backward up the winding road to the top of the hill. Then the film rolled forward, and the car began to descend the hill, out of control, brakes shot, picking up speed and then bursting through the guardrail and soaring over the cliff as Mommy shook me and shouted, &ldquo;Boys can&rsquo;t fly!&rdquo; The sedan tumbled through the air to the ground below, and right as Mommy slapped me again, the whole thing went <em>boom!</em></p>

<p>With each blow she told me to wake the hell up, and when I finally opened my eyes, I couldn&rsquo;t hear her voice any longer. Veins pushed from beneath the skin of her long, elegant, non-piano-playing fingers. Her earrings swung against her cheeks. Wisps of brown thread peeked from beneath her green cloth hair. At any moment I was sure Julio and his mommy would come downstairs and scold Mommy for handling so roughly a boy she loved, a boy she&rsquo;d fed and bathed and warmed, all with the same hands she was using now.</p>

<p>But my friend and his mother never came down.</p>

<p>It was just the three of us &mdash; me, Mommy, and Asia &mdash; on the sidewalk on that cold morning as my mother spoke to me without a sound, her lips forming the words <em>Can! You! Hear! Me! Can! You! Hear! Me!</em> The car sped toward the cliff, smashed through the rail, fell, and exploded over and over again, going <em>boom! boom! boom!</em> with each of my mother&rsquo;s blows to my head. Finally I shut my eyes against the blistering pain that filled my face and held on tight to the boy inside of me until it was all over.</p>
														</div>


				
